Commentary.Commentary: We are back for England's reply! The players are already out in the middle now. Zak Crawley and Ben Duckett are the two openers for England. Alzarri Joseph to start proceedings with three slips and a gully in place. Here we go...
... SECOND INNINGS ...

England, on the other hand, will be pleased with their bowling effort. The pitch looks like a good batting surface and the Windies' top order batters except for their skipper missed a trick or two to score more here. The pacers worked hard but didn't get any reward in the first hour, but once they got more information about the pitch, they got three before Lunch. The hosts added another two early in the second session including the big wicket of Kraigg Brathwaite. Then they struggled for a long time, but Chris Woakes broke the big partnership. He ended up with three while Mark Wood got a couple and Shoaib Bashir chipped in with one. Gus Atkinson was once again the pick of the bowlers with a four-wicket haul.

A mixed-bag batting performance from the Windies! They once again got off to a solid start as their openers stitched up a 76-run partnership before Mikyle Louis was removed. Skipper Kraigg Brathwaite held one end nicely and scored at a good rate as well, but he lost a couple of more partners before Lunch. The middle order also struggled a bit and the skipper was also dismissed after getting to his half-century. However, they fought back again through Jason Holder and Joshua Da Silva who added a crucial 109 runs to get them out of trouble. Holder brought up his fifty in the process but once he lost his partner, the Windies could not really add that many runs. The tail wagged around for a bit but they were ultimately bowled out for 282.

Commentary.Commentary: We are back! The umpires and the players take the field to start the Third Session on Day 1 of this 3rd Test match. West Indies batting first are 194/5 with Jason Holder and Joshua Da Silva at the crease building a partnership after losing a few quick wickets. ... DAY 1, LAST SESSION ...

SESSION SUMMARY - 97 runs and 2 wickets in 27 overs! It’s been a hard-fought session from both sides! England started strong, with Mark Wood delivering an excellent spell to dismiss the set Windies skipper. Kraigg Brathwaite might feel a bit unlucky, falling to a leg-side strangle after scoring a gritty half-century. Kavem Hodge didn't last long either, falling to Chris Woakes after a poor judgment. However, the visitors mounted a spirited fightback. Jason Holder looked solid from the outset, with Joshua Da Silva offering steady support. Initially, runs were hard to come by, but as the session progressed, they began finding the gaps and rotating the strike effectively, and have added 79 crucial runs together Despite a few close calls, they didn’t offer many chances to the English bowlers. They’ve navigated this session without further losses and will aim to build on this partnership post-Tea. Meanwhile, the hosts will be eager to strike early and wrap things up quickly. Join us for the third session at 8.30 pm IST (3 pm GMT).

Commentary.Commentary: We are back! Kraigg Brathwaite and Alick Athanaze are back on the crease to start the Second Session on Day 1. England finished the first session on a high and will be looking to continue the same momentum after Lunch. Mark Wood to start the proceedings. Let's Play!
... DAY 1, SECOND SESSION ...

Kirk McKenzie, batting at number three, showed intent with some elegant strokes, striking three boundaries against Atkinson. However, his promising start was cut short by Mark Wood, who cleaned him up for 12 in the following over. This dismissal jolted the West Indies, who were looking to consolidate after the loss of the first wicket. Alick Athanaze then joined Brathwaite at the crease, hoping to stabilize the innings. However, his stay was brief and disappointing. Attempting to play a pull shot, Athanaze ended up dragging the ball onto his stumps for just two runs, a dismissal that came right on the stroke of Lunch and further dented the West Indies' prospects. West Indies won the toss and elected to bat first, with Brathwaite and Louis opening the innings. The English bowlers extracted plenty of movement with the brand-new cherry, repeatedly beating the bat and creating numerous opportunities. Despite the early movement, the openers managed to survive initially, only for England to bounce back strongly in the latter part of the session. Stay tuned for the exciting Second session coming your way. Join us back at 6.10 pm IST (12.40 pm GMT)

West Indies captain Kraigg Brathwaite and his opening partner Mikyle Louis managed to survive the challenging opening hour. Brathwaite, looking solid at the crease, capitalized on loose deliveries, while Louis took his time to settle in. The duo's resilience saw them take their partnership past the 50-run mark, frustrating the English bowlers who consistently beat the bat without initial success. Brathwaite reached his 30th Test fifty with a composed knock off 70 balls, a testament to his steady hand at the top of the order. The breakthrough for England came when Gus Atkinson, maintaining his impressive form, induced an edge from Louis, who was caught behind for 26. This ended a 76-run opening stand and provided the much-needed breakthrough for the hosts.

England get the third wicket in the second hour of the first session of Day 1 as the players and the Umpires walk off for LUNCH. Lunch on day one of the third Test has been called, and West Indies find themselves at 97/3 after 26 overs. After a promising start, England's disciplined bowling turned the tide, leaving the West Indies in a precarious position. The English camp is all smiles as they head into the break, having successfully built pressure and reaped the rewards.

TOSS - The coin lands in favour of Kraigg Brathwaite. West Indies have elected to BAT first.​​​​

In reply, the West Indies fought hard and secured a valuable 31-run first-innings lead, amassing 457 runs in 111.5 overs. Kavem Hodge’s maiden Test century and Alick Athanaze’s excellent 82 were crucial. Contributions from Kraigg Brathwaite, Joshua Da Silva, and Shamar Joseph, with Da Silva’s unbeaten 82, bolstered their score. Chris Woakes was the pick of the English bowlers with a four-wicket haul, while Gus Atkinson and Shoaib Bashir took two wickets each, and Stokes and Mark Wood chipped in with one each. In their second innings, England recovered from an early loss of Zak Crawley, with Duckett and Pope laying the foundation with half-centuries. Harry Brook and Joe Root then slammed magnificent hundreds to push the West Indies on the back foot. Despite losing quick wickets towards the end, England posted 425 in 92.2 overs. Jayden Seales was the most successful Windies bowler with four wickets, while Alzarri Joseph, Jason Holder, Shamar Joseph, and Sinclair took one wicket each. Chasing 385 to level the series, the West Indies crumbled in their second innings skittled out for just 143 in 36.1 overs. Only four batters reached double figures, with skipper Brathwaite’s 47 being the highest. Shoaib Bashir claimed his maiden Test fifer, leading England to a comprehensive victory. Woakes and Atkinson each took two wickets, and Wood picked up one. As England look to complete a series whitewash, can the West Indies salvage some pride and end their tour on a high note? Stay tuned for Toss and other exciting match updates.

The West Indies, meanwhile, have been forced to make a couple of changes in their squad. Fast bowler Jeremiah Louis, who was sidelined with a hamstring injury during the second Test at Trent Bridge, has been ruled out of the final game. Kevin Sinclair took a fiery Mark Wood bouncer and has suffered a fracture on his left forearm. Akeem Jordan, who has played cricket in the UK, was named Louis' replacement. Jordan has yet to make his debut in Test cricket but has experience in white-ball formats. In a boost for the visitors, Gudakesh Motie has recovered from the illness that kept him out of the Nottingham Test and is available for selection. The series opener at Lord's was a complete decimation. England defeated the West Indies by an innings and 114 runs, thanks to Gus Atkinson's record-breaking debut spell and a memorable farewell for James Anderson. The second Test saw the West Indies put up a better fight, but England proved too strong, winning by a massive 241 runs to secure the series with a game to spare. In the second Test, England were put into bat first and posted a formidable 416 runs in 88.3 overs on the first day. Ollie Pope top-scored with a scintillating century, supported by half-centuries from Ben Duckett and Ben Stokes. Contributions from Harry Brook, Jamie Smith, and Chris Woakes pushed the total past 400. Alzarri Joseph was the standout bowler for the West Indies, taking three wickets, while Jayden Seales, Kavem Hodge, and Kevin Sinclair took two wickets each, and Shamar Joseph picked up one.

The English Test Summer intensifies as England take on the West Indies in the third and final Test of the series at the iconic Edgbaston in Birmingham. The Ben Stokes-led England side has already secured the Richards-Botham Trophy with an unassailable 2-0 lead. England has named an unchanged squad for this fixture, although Dan Lawrence has shifted to the Men's Hundred to lead the London Spirit. The rest of the squad will complete their national duties before joining the entertaining format.

His aggressive batting added crucial runs before he holed out, bringing the innings to a close.

So, play will be extended upto 11.17 pm IST (5.47 pm GMT). Jamie Smith walks out with Chris Woakes to bat for England. Jayden Seales to start the attack after Tea for West Indies. Let's Play!
Oh no! Just as the Umpires and the players were about to walk in to start the Last session, the rain gods showed their appearance. The start of the last session stands delayed.
... DAY 2, FINAL SESSION ...

The duo added over 50 runs and took them closer to the Windies' total, but it was Gudakesh Motie who got the big wicket of Root on 87 and denied him a chance of a hundred. However, that did not stop Smith from playing his shots freely and to be honest, he was also helped by some wayward bowling from the visitors. Chris Woakes also came in and managed to chip in without much trouble and the lead has been cut short to just 8 runs. England will look to go past that and take as much lead as possible while West Indies will want to stop them from doing that. Join us at 8.30 pm IST (3 pm GMT) to catch all the exciting action in the last session.

SESSION SUMMARY - 117 runs and 2 wickets in 26 overs! Just like Day 1, the second session has been a great battle between the two teams. The hosts started with two set batters at the crease and both Ben Stokes and Joe Root put a good stand of 115 runs and reduced the deficit by a good margin. Skipper took an aggressive approach and notched up his fifty but the short-ball plan against him worked for the visitors. Root held one end solidly and found excellent support from Jamie Smith who has shown great maturity throughout this series.

As the session drew to a close, Root remained unbeaten on 58, while Stokes approached his half-century, standing firm on 48. Their steadfast partnership has not only stabilized England's innings but also set the stage for a potentially strong response in the remainder of the day. With the score at 157/5, the hosts are now in a much better position to build a substantial total. The afternoon session promises to be an intriguing battle as England aims to close the deficit and the West Indies look for wickets to regain control. Stay tuned for more action from this captivating Test match at Edgbaston. Join us back again at 6.10 pm IST (12.40 pm GMT) for the Second Session.

The day began with Joe Root and Ollie Pope resuming their innings. West Indies struck early, with Shamar Joseph removing Pope for 10 in the third over of the day. Jayden Seales then claimed the wicket of Harry Brook, who edged to the keeper for just two, leaving England in a precarious position. Things could have been even better for the visitors if they took a review for Joe Root as he was out LBW. Captain Ben Stokes joined Root at the crease and together, they embarked on a recovery mission. Root, displaying his usual composure and elegance, played some exquisite strokes. During his innings, he surpassed Brian Lara's tally of Test runs, marking yet another milestone in his illustrious career. The partnership between Root and Stokes flourished, surpassing the 50-run mark and gradually shifting the momentum. Root brought up yet another fifty in Test cricket, showcasing his consistency and class. Both Root and Stokes appeared unfazed by the West Indies bowlers, who struggled to find breakthroughs. Their partnership grew past 100 runs, leaving the visitors searching for answers.

Commentary.Commentary: We are all set! The umpires and the players are out in the field to start Day 2 of this Test match. Joe Root walks out with Ollie Pope to start England's innings from 38/3 after 8 overs. Shamar Joseph will start the attack for West Indies on Day 2. Let's Play!

In response, England’s openers Zak Crawley and Ben Duckett faced a challenging task. Jayden Seales struck first, removing Crawley for 18 and breaking the 29-run opening stand. Duckett chopped one onto the stumps for just three. Mark Wood, sent in as a nightwatchman, edged to second slip without scoring. Ollie Pope and Joe Root remained unbeaten on six and two, respectively, as England ended a tumultuous day on 38/3. As the teams prepare for the second day, both will be eager to seize control. England will aim to stabilize and build a substantial innings, while West Indies will look to capitalize on their strong start. It's poised to be another fascinating day of Test cricket, with the potential for dramatic twists and turns. Stay tuned as the action unfolds at Edgbaston.

The day began with West Indies winning the toss and opting to bat first. Kraigg Brathwaite and Mikyle Louis provided a solid foundation, surviving the first hour with composed decision-making. Despite plenty of movement from the English bowlers, the openers took their stand past 50. Brathwaite reached a well-composed fifty off 70 balls, showcasing his resilience. The breakthrough came in the 22nd over when Gus Atkinson had Louis edging to the keeper, ending a 76-run opening stand. Kirk McKenzie came in and played positively but was cleaned up by Mark Wood for 12. Alick Athanaze, trying to pull, ended up dragging one back onto the stumps, falling for just two right on the stroke of lunch. Brathwaite, looking good at the crease, was dismissed for 61 soon after lunch. Kavem Hodge, leaving one alone, was bowled for 13, leaving West Indies at 115/5. Jason Holder and Joshua Da Silva then led a commendable recovery. Both batters looked solid, guiding their team to tea without further damage. Holder brought up his fifty off 92 balls, and the partnership grew to over 100 runs. Chris Woakes finally broke the 109-run stand, with Da Silva falling just one short of his fifty. Alzarri Joseph played aggressively but was dismissed for 15 after attempting one shot too many. Holder, after a valiant 59, was cleaned up by Atkinson with a beauty. Shamar Joseph added a useful 16 at number 11, but the English bowlers wrapped up the innings for 282 in 75.1 overs. Atkinson finished with a four-fer, while Woakes picked up three crucial wickets.

England stuck to their strategy in the final session and were finally rewarded when Chris Woakes dismissed Joshua Da Silva. ​​​​Alzarri Joseph came in and hit a few lusty blows before getting out. Jason Holder managed to reach his half-century, but with partners falling at the other end, he became more tentative and was eventually dismissed by a brilliant ball from Gus Atkinson. The tail managed to hang around and add about 30 runs, bringing the total to 282. However, they knew that with more contributions from the top order, they could have capitalized better on a good wicket. When England's openers came out, they started aggressively, playing shots freely. However, the mood in the stadium quickly shifted when Zak Crawley and Ben Duckett fell on consecutive deliveries, and the nightwatchman, Mark Wood also sent back giving the Windies a renewed sense of hope.

The second session was an intense battle as both sides fought hard. England seized the early initiative when Mark Wood dismissed the Windies skipper, who had already reached a half-century, and Chris Woakes quickly followed with another wicket. However, Jason Holder and Joshua Da Silva then took control. They ensured no further wickets fell and, once set, began to score freely. The pair added 79 runs in the session. Ben Stokes tried various strategies, including a short-ball plan and bringing on Shoaib Bashir to tempt the batters, but aside from a few play-and-miss moments, nothing worked. As they headed into tea, England knew they needed to come up with different tactics.

After winning the toss, Kraigg Brathwaite chose to bat first on what appeared to be a great batting wicket. The openers looked solid in the opening hour, successfully negotiating the initial spells from England’s pacers. However, the opening stand was finally broken at 76, but England had to work hard for it. Before lunch, they managed to add Alick Athanaze ​​​​​​and Kirk Mckenzie to their tally, gaining a firm grip on the game. Gus Atkinson made the initial breakthrough, followed by a beautiful delivery from Mark Wood for his first wicket. Atkinson capped off the session with another scalp to his name on the stroke of Lunch.

A fantastic Day 1 comes to a close! Session Summary - 126 runs and 8 wickets in 30.1 overs. The West Indian bowlers have compensated for their top-order shortcomings with a stellar performance. Jayden Seales was exceptional in his brief spell, taking a couple of crucial wickets, while Alzarri Joseph provided solid support removing one. England would not have expected to end Day 1 in this position and now faces an uphill battle to get back into the game. Earlier in the day, the Windies batters showed flashes of brilliance, but now that total of 282 looms large for the hosts.

England now have a straightforward task ahead, needing just 82 runs to whitewash the series. For the West Indies, their only hope lies in taking quick wickets to delay the inevitable. Stay tuned as the chase is set to begin shortly.

The West Indies’ innings saw promising starts from their batters, but none could convert these into substantial scores. Mikyle Louis (57) and Kavem Hodge (55) both notched up fifties, yet the rest of the batting lineup faltered, contributing to the modest total of 175. The lower-order batters succumbed to the reverse swing, and Mark Wood was fantastic with the ball, claiming a fifer and dismantling the visitors with his pace. Gus Atkinson supported well, taking two wickets, while Chris Woakes, Shoaib Bashir, and Ben Stokes each chipped in with a wicket.

Mark Wood, you beauty! He has bowled one of the fine reverse swing spells here and completely dismantled the Windies lower order. The Winfdies have been swiftly bundled out for 175 in 51.6 overs, leaving England a target of just 82 runs to clean-sweep the series. Mark Wood leads his team off the field to a standing ovation, having delivered an exceptional bowling performance.

As we head into the afternoon session, the match hangs in a delicate balance. England will look to capitalize on their breakthroughs, while the West Indies aim to build on their lead and set a challenging target. An exciting session of Test cricket awaits! Join us back at 6.10 pm IST (12.40 pm GMT) for the start of the second session on Day 3.

The day began with Mikyle Louis and Alick Athanaze resuming their innings for the West Indies. Both batsmen looked comfortable and survived the early pressure from the English bowlers. However, Bashir made a crucial breakthrough by trapping Athanaze in front of the stumps for 12, bringing Kavem Hodge to the crease. Hodge immediately looked positive, scoring freely and keeping the scoreboard ticking. Louis, at the other end, continued his good form, and the pair quickly put together a 50-run partnership. Louis reached his maiden Test fifty in style, hitting a maximum off Bashir, and played some delightful strokes that took the West Indies into the lead. However, the ball started to reverse, and English skipper Ben Stokes took advantage, dismissing Louis for 57 and breaking the promising 72-run stand. Jason Holder then came to the crease, looking solid in defense, but Gus Atkinson soon trapped him LBW for 11. Joshua Da Silva joined Hodge, who continued his composed innings. Hodge reached his well-deserved fifty, anchoring the innings as the West Indies approached lunch. Both Hodge and Da Silva remained unbeaten on 53 and 2 respectively, guiding their team to 151/5 at the end of the morning session with a lead of 57 runs.

SESSION SUMMARY - 27 OVERS, 118 RUNS, 3 WICKETS. Lunch on day three, and what a session it has been! A balanced morning, but England still holds the edge in this compelling Test match. West Indies have added 118 runs in 27 overs for the loss of three wickets, taking their score to 151/5 at the end of 41 overs, leading England by 57 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: All in readiness for the start of Day 3! The players make their way out to the middle now and this will be a crucial day in deciding this Test match. Alick Athanaze and Mikyle Louis are the overnight batters for West Indies. Shoaib Bashir will start proceedings with some offices. Let's play...

In their second innings, the West Indies had a disastrous start. Skipper Kraigg Brathwaite was dismissed for a duck in the very first over by Chris Woakes, and Kirk McKenzie’s struggles continued as he was caught behind for eight. At the close of Day Two, Mikyle Louis and Alick Athanaze remained unbeaten on 18 and 5, with the West Indies on 33/2, still trailing by 61 runs. As Day Three dawns at Edgbaston, both teams will be eager to seize control. England will aim to capitalize on their strong position, while the West Indies will look to recover and fight their way back into the match. An intriguing day of Test cricket awaits so stay tuned as we bring you all the exciting action from England vs West Indies 3rd Test Day 3.

Day Two began with England's Joe Root and Ollie Pope at the crease. Shamar Joseph provided an early breakthrough for the West Indies, dismissing Pope for 10. Harry Brook followed soon after, edging one to the keeper for just two runs. Despite these early setbacks, Root remained solid and found a reliable partner in skipper Ben Stokes. The West Indies bowlers struggled to maintain pressure, allowing Root and Stokes to build a crucial partnership. Root surpassed Brian Lara on the all-time Test runs tally, bringing up his 63rd Test fifty in the process. The duo took England past the 50-run mark and continued to accumulate runs with ease, finding gaps for singles and occasional boundaries. After tea, Stokes reached his fifty but soon fell for 54, with Alzarri Joseph breaking the 115-run stand through a well-executed short-ball strategy. Root continued to anchor the innings, joined by Jamie Smith, and kept the scoreboard ticking. Root's innings came to an end at 87 when he was trapped in front by Gudakesh Motie, missing out on a well-deserved century. Chris Woakes then joined Smith at the crease, and together they forged a solid partnership, with Smith bringing up his second Test fifty off just 60 balls. Smith and Woakes added 106 runs for the eighth wicket, propelling England into a commanding lead. Smith fell five runs short of his maiden Test century, cleaned up by Shamar Joseph. Woakes, who brought up his seventh Test fifty, was dismissed for 62. Gus Atkinson provided a late flourish with a 16-ball 21 before England were bowled out for 376.

A warm welcome to everyone joining us here today. As we begin Day Three of this thrilling Test match, England holds the upper hand after a dominant performance on the second day. The hosts managed to secure a handy lead of 94 runs before their bowlers came out firing, reducing the West Indies to 33/2 at the close of play. The visitors still trail by 61 runs and face a daunting task ahead.
... DAY 3, FIRST SESSION ...

Right then, that is it from a spectacular Day 2 of this 3rd Test. England have made a fine comeback and now are in a strong position while Windies need to do lot more work to get back in this game. Action on Day 3 which is called the 'Moving Day' will start on 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT), buy you can join us early for all the build-up. Cheers!

It was a very eventful last session and the crowd remained entertained on every other ball. Jamie Smith and Chris Woakes extended their partnership and managed to take the lead. The former was scoring at a good rate and soon got into the nervous 90s. However, unfortunately for him, he lost his wicket just five short of his maiden ton but Woakes stayed there and registered his fifty putting the hosts into a healthy lead. Gus Atkinson played a few lusty blows towards the end and they ended up with 94-run lead. After coming onto bat, disaster hit the Windies straight away as they lost skipper Kraigg Brathwaite in the very first over for nothing while Kirk Mckenzie also could not make much impact and ended his series on a disappointing note. Mikyle Louis and Alick Athanaze made sure that they do not lose any more wickets and saw the remaining of the session out.

The second session was evenly matched, with both teams having their share of success. Ben Stokes reached his half-century before being dismissed, but not before his partnership with Joe Root had significantly reduced the deficit. After Stokes' departure, Root found a solid partner in Jamie Smith, who looked impressive right from the start. Unfortunately, Root fell for 87, narrowly missing another century. Smith continued to score freely, and Chris Woakes added valuable runs, ensuring that they went into Tea without losing any more wickets. The Windies seemed a bit unsettled but persisted with their short-ball strategy, which paid off against the English skipper, thanks to Alzarri Joseph. Gudakesh Motie once again managed to remove Root, which was a crucial wicket, but the hosts were able to build another partnership. Heading into the final session, the West Indies only had an 8-run lead.

England started Day 2 in a tough spot, and losing Ollie Pope and Harry Brook within the first hour put them even further behind. The situation could have been worse if the West Indies had reviewed an LBW decision against Joe Root, who would have been out for zero. Missing that review proved costly. However, Root, along with his skipper, formed a vital partnership that steadied the innings without losing more wickets in that session. For the West Indies, Shamar Joseph secured an early breakthrough, followed by another wicket from Jayden Seales, but they failed to capitalize on this momentum, allowing the hosts to recover.

What a turnaround for England! From a precarious 54/5, sensational batting from Joe Root, Jamie Smith, Ben Stokes, and Chris Woakes propelled them to a 94-run lead. West Indies have only themselves to blame—firstly for missing a crucial review on Root, and then for neither their bowlers nor batters stepping up. Now, they find themselves trailing significantly by 61 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: What a memorable series it's been! England bid farewell to the legendary James Anderson with a victory in the first game and then went on to secure a clean sweep against the Windies. Ben Stokes, the English skipper, has just received the Richards-Botham Trophy, and the team is celebrating together with some photos. Some of the England players will now head off to join their teams in The Hundred 2024, while others will enjoy a well-earned rest. Meanwhile, the West Indies will be gearing up for a two-match Test series against South Africa, starting on Wednesday, August 7th. Be sure to join us early for all the pre-match build-up. Until then, take care and goodbye!

Ben Stokes, the victorious skipper of England praises Mark Wood's spell, calling it amazing and acknowledging Wood's incredible effort whenever he dons the England shirt. Stokes highlights Wood's skill and speed, noting how he creates pressure even when not taking wickets. He enjoys pairing Wood with Bash due to their contrasting speeds and is delighted with Wood's performance. Stokes commends newcomers Gus Atkinson and Jamie Smith for their impressive debuts. He praises Atkinson's 12-wicket haul and Smith's exceptional batting and wicketkeeping. Stokes notes the team's improved ability to assess conditions and make smart choices, contrasting their current approach to how they would have responded 18 or 20 months ago. He concludes by emphasizing the team's focus on winning and their pride in representing England, always aiming for victory with the three lions on their chest.

Kraigg Brathwaite, the captain of West Indies says that 280 was not good enough on a wicket that suited batting, but they did well with the ball. Adds the communication between the guys was a bit down and they were not able to put pressure on the batters for longer periods. Tells that they were just not consistent enough with hitting the top of off like they were in Australia. Says that the thing that he liked the most in this series was that never gave up, and always tried to fight their way out of difficult situations. Mentions that Jayden Seales was good in patches and Motie did well too, but a longer break between the games would have helped a bit. Further adds that they are now looking forward to the two Tests against South Africa and it is important that they show growth and learn from their mistakes.

Jayden Seales is the PLAYER OF THE SERIES FOR WEST INDIES for his good bowling performances picking up a total of 13 wickets. He expresses pride in representing his team. He emphasizes the importance of his comeback in the series and the deliberate decision to play at Sussex to adapt to English conditions. Seales acknowledges the challenge of facing opponents who play freely and seize opportunities. He believes that with continuous learning and growth, the West Indies will become a formidable force. Despite the physical demands, he feels his body is holding up well and looks forward to recovering in time for the tour to South Africa.

Gus Atkinson is the PLAYER OF THE SERIES FOR ENGLAND for his amazing bowling efforts and picking up a total of 22 wickets. He feels honored to have taken 22 wickets. Without high expectations initially, he finds this achievement particularly special. Reflecting on the series, he describes it as an incredible and unforgettable experience. Atkinson credits his success to running in hard, hitting the wicket, swinging the ball in different situations, and utilizing the crease. He looks forward to playing against Sri Lanka next. He expresses joy in bowling alongside Mark Wood, appreciating his advice and finding Wood's performance particularly inspiring. Atkinson cherishes the series and eagerly anticipates the future.

Mark Wood is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH for his seven wickets including a stunning fifer in the second innings. He expresses relief and gratitude. He mentions feeling down initially but credits Jimmy for a motivational talk during the break, which helped him refocus on his strengths. Wood highlights the confidence boost from his first wicket, stating he adapted to conditions by concentrating on bowling fast as per Stokes' directive. Despite fluctuating speeds due to injuries, he commits to maintaining pace throughout the summer. He emphasizes the importance of mindset, especially while bowling with a reversing ball, and appreciates his team's unwavering support. Wood acknowledges the challenge of back-to-back Tests and thanks the physio for keeping him fit.
Presentation Time...

Chasing a paltry total of 82, England had a new opening pair, as Zak Crawley had gone for scans on his right index finger. Skipper Ben Stokes opened alongside Ben Duckett. Stokes made his intentions clear, starting aggressively and hitting boundaries for fun. The visitors failed to contain the English skipper, who raced to fifty in just 24 balls, bringing up the fastest fifty for England in Tests. Duckett also found boundaries as both made short work of the chase. Stokes and Duckett remained unbeaten on 57 and 25, respectively, as England chased down the total in just 7.2 overs with 10 wickets in hand.

West Indies lost Brathwaite (0) and Kirk McKenzie (8) cheaply in the evening session of day two. Alick Athanaze (12) looked good but departed the next morning. Mikyle Louis and Kavem Hodge built a solid 72-run stand before the former fell on 57 after notching up his maiden Test fifty. Hodge played some wonderful strokes and brought up his fifty, but lacked support from the other end. It was a short stay for Jason Holder (12) at the crease. The ball started reversing, and Mark Wood dismissed Joshua Da Silva (5) and Alzarri Joseph (2) in quick succession. Hodge (55), Jayden Seales (0), and Shamar Joseph (4) were sent packing in a single over by Wood, who picked up a fifer as West Indies were bundled out for 175 in 52 overs.

In reply, England lost three wickets in quick succession and were tottering at 54/5 on the second morning before Joe Root (87) and skipper Ben Stokes (54) led the recovery. Both played beautifully, keeping the Windies at bay. Another solid 106-run stand between Jamie Smith (95) and Woakes (62) helped England gain a lead of 94. For the Windies, Alzarri Joseph picked up a four-fer but was expensive, while Jayden Seales and Shamar Joseph chipped in with three and two scalps, respectively.

England have completely outplayed the West Indies in the third and final Test, securing a clean sweep and starting their men's international summer outstandingly. All smiles in the English camp as their skipper led from the front in the chase of 82, completing it in just 7.2 overs. England beat the West Indies by 10 wickets, whitewashing the Caribbean side. Let's recap this Test match. West Indies won the toss and opted to bat first. Skipper Kraigg Brathwaite (61) played a solid knock at the top, stitching a good partnership with fellow opener Mikyle Louis (26). England stormed back into the contest with quick wickets, but Jason Holder (59) and Joshua Da Silva (49) stitched a brilliant 109-run stand for the sixth wicket. England broke the stand and quickly wrapped up the Windies’ tail, knocking them over for 282. Gus Atkinson picked up four wickets for England, while Chris Woakes grabbed three.

A statement series whitewash for England! We can say that 'Bazball' is well and truly revolutionizing Test cricket here. The English skipper led the chase from the front and broke the record of the fastest fifty for an English player in this format. However, the credit must go to that scintillating spell from Mark Wood that set up this victory for the hosts. West Indies can take a few positives from this series and this will be a great learning curve for the not-so-experienced Windies side.
